I"õm<p><strong>Seed Metaphor</strong></p>

<p>An operating system is a seed. The â€œkernelâ€ of the seed is the core of the operating system, providing operating system services to applications programs, which is surrounded by the â€œshellâ€ of the seed that is what users see from the outside.</p>

<p>Some people want to tie â€œkernelâ€ (and, indeed, â€œshellâ€) down to be more specific than that. But in truth thereâ€™s a lot of variation across operating systems. Not the least these variations is what constitutes a â€œshellâ€ (which can range from Solarisâ€™ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">sh</code> through Netwareâ€™s Console Command Interpreter to OS/2â€™s Workplace Shell and Windows NTâ€™s Explorer), but thereâ€™s also a lot of variance from one operating system to another in what is, and isnâ€™t, a part of a â€œkernelâ€ (which may or may not include disk I/O, for example).</p>

<p>There are other terminologies. In IBM mainframe terminology, the â€œkernelâ€ in the seed/nut metaphor is called the control program. Other names include the supervisor, the monitor, the core, and the executive. Core is another fairly obvious biological metaphor. It is interesting that so too is another name. Harvey M. Deitel, in his Operating Systems, calls the control program the nucleus. The word â€œnucleusâ€ comes from the Latin nucleus, and means the kernel of a nut (c.f. the Latin nux, which means â€œnutâ€). So even calling the control program â€œthe nucleusâ€ is in fact making this same operating-system-as-a-nut analogy. Itâ€™s an analogy that is used for more than just operating systems. If you are familiar with chemistry, for example, youâ€™ll know that an atomic nucleus is surrounded by electrons in shells.</p>

<p>The kernel does all the interaction with the hardware, and manages the memory, the I/O devices.</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>That part of the system which permanently resides in main storage has historically been called the nucleus. The nucleus will usually consist of a minimal set of primitives and processes for the management of processes, resources, and input-output</p>
</blockquote>

