<p><strong>Job</strong></p>

<p>A shell provides an interface to handle processes. It does so with the help of an abstraction call <strong>jobs</strong>.</p>

<p>Any program you interactively start that doesnâ€™t detach from the terminal (ie, not a daemon) is a job. To list all the jobs you are running, you can useÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">jobs</code>.</p>

<p>Some programs are not designed to be run with continuous user input and disconnect from the terminal at the first opportunity. For example, a web server responds to web requests, rather than user input. Mail servers are another example of this type of application. These types of programs are known asÂ daemons.Â they typically handle things such as network requests (ssh server), hardware activity, and otherÂ wait &amp; watchÂ type tasks  (e.g. firewalls, docker daemon).</p>

<p>The shell has the concept of â€œforegroundâ€ jobs and â€œbackgroundâ€ jobs. <strong>Foreground jobs are process groups</strong> with control of the terminal, and background jobs are process groups without control of the terminal. If youâ€™re running an interactive program, you can pressÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Ctrl+Z</code>Â to suspend it. Then you can start it back in the foreground (usingÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">fg</code>) or in the background (usingÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">bg</code>). While the program is suspended or running in the background, you can start another program - you would then have two jobs running. You can also start a program running in the background by appending an <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&amp;</code> like this:Â <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">program &amp;</code>. That program would become a background job.</p>

<p>The shell creates a process group within the current session for each â€œjobâ€ it launches, and places each process it starts into the appropriate process group. For example,Â <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">ls | head</code> is a pipeline of two processes, which the shell considers a single job, and will belong to a single, new process group.</p>

<p>Each terminal has a <strong>foreground process group</strong>. to which it sends signals generated by keyboard interrupts, notably <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">SIGINT</code> (â€œinterruptâ€, <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Control+C</code>), <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">SIGTSTP</code> (â€œterminal stopâ€, <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Control+Z</code>), and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">SIGQUIT</code> (â€œquitâ€, <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Control+\</code>). It also sends the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">SIGTTIN</code> and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">SIGTTOU</code> signals to any processes that attempt to read from or write to the terminal and that are not in the foreground process group. The shell, in turn, partitions the command pipelines that it creates into process groups, and controls what process group is the foreground process group of its controlling terminal, thus determining what processes (and thus what command pipelines) may perform I/O to and from the terminal at any given time.</p>

<p>When the shell forks a new child process for a command pipeline, both the parent shell process and the child process immediately make the child process into the leader of the process group for the command pipeline. In this way, it is ensured that the child is the leader of the process group before either the parent or the child relies on this being the case.</p>

<p>When bringing a job to the foreground, the shell sets it as the terminalâ€™s foreground process group; when putting a job to the background, the shell sets the terminalâ€™s foreground process group to another process group or itself.</p>

<p>Processes may read from and write to their controlling terminal if they are in the foreground process group. Otherwise they receiveÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">SIGTTIN</code>Â andÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">SIGTTOU</code>Â signals on attempts to read from and write to the terminal respectively. By default these signals suspend the process, although most shells maskÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">SIGTTOU</code>Â so that a background job can write to the terminal uninterrupted.</p>

<p>There is no key combination to send SIGSTOP. Control-S tells the terminal driver to suspend output, but does not send a signal to the process. Control-Q resumes output. <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Control+C</code>Â (control characterÂ intr) sends <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">SIGINT</code> which will interrupt the application. Usually causing it to abort, but this is up to the application to decide. <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Control+Z</code>Â (control characterÂ susp) sends <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">SIGTSTP</code> to a foreground application, effectively putting it in the background, suspended. This is useful if you need to break out of something like an editor to go and grab some data you needed. You can go back into the application by runningÂ fgÂ (orÂ %xÂ whereÂ xÂ is the job number as shown inÂ jobs).</p>

<p>Itâ€™s worth adding that itâ€™s also possible to runÂ bgÂ (instead ofÂ fg) to unsuspend an application thatâ€™s been Ctrl+Zâ€™edÂ withoutÂ putting it back into the foreground; effectively giving you control of both the shell that started the applicationÂ andÂ the application itself, as if you had usedÂ &amp;Â when starting the application. This often comes in handy when you forgot to start it withÂ &amp;</p>

<p><strong>How are daemons spawned?: init or orphans</strong>Daemons areÂ spawned one of two ways: either the init process forks and createsÂ them directly â€“ like we mentioned above in theÂ init processÂ segment â€“Â or some otherÂ process will fork itself to create a child process, and then the parent process immediately exits. The first condition seems pretty straightforward â€“ the init process forks to create a daemon â€“ but how does that second conditionÂ work, and how doesÂ the init process end up becoming the parent of these daemons?Â When youÂ fork a process to create a child process, and then immediately kill that parent process,Â theÂ child process becomesÂ anÂ orphaned processÂ â€“ a running process with no parent (not to be confused with aÂ zombie process, such asÂ a child process that has been terminated but is waiting on the parentÂ process to read its exit status). By default, if a child process gets orphaned, the init process will automatically adopt the process and become its parent. This is a key concept to understand, because this is normally how daemons that you start after boot up relate to the init process.Â </p>

<p><strong>How are background jobs different from daemons?</strong> DaemonÂ differ from simple background processes that are spawned in the terminal because these background process are typically bound to that terminal session, and when that terminal session ends itÂ will send the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">SIGHUP</code> messageÂ to all background processes â€“ which normally terminatesÂ them. Because daemons are normally children of the init process, itâ€™s more difficult to terminateÂ them. If I start a program in the background using <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&amp;</code> (for example <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">./script &amp;</code> ), what makes this processâ€™ execution different than if I ran normally a program that turns itself into a daemon? Running a program in the background, it no longer is directly controlled by the terminal (you canâ€™t simplyÂ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">^C</code>Â it), but it can still write to the terminal and interfere with your work. Typically a daemon will separate itself from the terminal (in addition to forking) and its output/error would be redirected to files. Does this simply mean that if I logout the background process will stop and the daemon will keep running? The background process could be protected withÂ nohupÂ but unless its output were redirected (no hup does it, no?), closing the terminal would prevent it from writing, producing an error that likely would stop it.  Besides the problem of keeping track of the programâ€™s output (and error messages), thereâ€™s the problem of restarting it if it happens to die. A service script fits into the way the other services on the system are designed, providing a more/less standard way of controlling the daemon.</p>

